// dense.su — a TRAINABLE dense (Linear) layer on the Sutra substrate (learned-decoder D1).
//
// h = matmul(W, x) + b      (W: out×in, x: in, b: out)
//
// The weights W and b arrive as PARAMETERS (the same runtime-parameter discipline the hero
// render uses for θ, but matrices), so a host optimizer trains them by autograd THROUGH the
// compiled substrate `matmul` — every op runs on the substrate; only the optimizer is
// host-side. This is the trainable cell the learned coordinate-MLP decoder (D3) stacks.
function vector dense(vector W, vector x, vector b) {
    return matmul(W, x) + b;
}

// Activated variant for stacking into an MLP: a CUBIC nonlinearity h³ via hadamard.
//
// FINDING (D1, 2026-06-17): the substrate's `tanh`/`sin` operate on the canonical complex-
// vector form (fuzzy values), NOT elementwise over an arbitrary length-H activation buffer —
// `tanh(matmul(W,x))` on a vector raises a dim-mismatch in `_canon`. So the MLP nonlinearity
// is a HADAMARD POLYNOMIAL, which IS elementwise on real field buffers (the same machinery the
// hero/button fields use). Cubic is odd (sign-preserving) and differentiable everywhere;
// expressivity for image fitting comes from Fourier-feature inputs + these layers (D2/D3).
function vector dense_cube(vector W, vector x, vector b) {
    vector h = matmul(W, x) + b;
    return hadamard(hadamard(h, h), h);
}

// SIREN-style activated variant: a SIN nonlinearity, now that `sin_buf` makes sin elementwise
// over an activation buffer (compiler primitive, 2026-06-17 — the D1 finding above is what
// blocked this until now). h = sin(matmul(W,x) + b), the activation running on the substrate
// (sin_buf = periodic table readout, autograd-preserving). The SIREN frequency ω is folded into
// W at init (the standard trick), so the layer body itself is just sin of the affine map.
function vector dense_sin(vector W, vector x, vector b) {
    return sin_buf(matmul(W, x) + b);
}

// Self-contained sanity: tanh(1) = 0.7616 (matmul of matrices is exercised via the host
// wrapper / tests, where W,x,b are real torch tensors — `.su` literals are scalars only).
function vector main() {
    return tanh(make_real(1.0));
}
